In Tables 1 and 2 we report the clarity score and the NDCG@10 metrics, respectively, for the tested query recommendation systems, according to the Substitution evaluation protocol. For each system, collection, and metric, we report the minimum and maximum metric values across the six generated recommendations, as well as their average values and the standard deviations.
According to the SCS metric, our GQR systems get the highest values with both the worst and the best performing recommendations on the Robust04 dataset, outperformed only by System 2’s best recommendation on the ClueWeb09B dataset, but by a small margin. However, on average, our proposed GQR (GPT-3) system outperforms all other methods, including the commercial systems. Moreover, the corresponding standard deviation values are the smallest, meaning that all the generated query recommendation obtain a similar, high SCS score.
According to the NDCG@10 metric, our proposed GQR (GPT-3) system outperforms all other systems. With respect to the best competitor, namely System 2, our experiments show that GQR (GPT-3) has, on average, a +23% and a +27% improvement in NDCG@10 on Robust04 and ClueWeb09B, respectively. As with the SCS metric, the standard deviation of the NDCG@10 scores across the six generated recommendations is small, so the recommendations get a NDCG@10 score concentrated around the average value.

To further investigate on this topic, we extracted 200 rare queries from the tail distribution of the AOL query log, thus considering the queries with a frequency equal to 1-2 in the query log.

RQ4: What is the impact of the number of examples in the prompt context on the performance of our GQR system?
<br class="ltx_break"/>
To assess this RQ we conduct a prompt study on Robust04, in which we compare prompts with a different number of examples in it.
This prompt study analyzes the impact of the number of examples in the prompt on the performance in terms of SCS and NDCG@10
Our results, reported in Table 7, shows that the model with a single example in the prompt achieves comparable performances with the prompt with up to 10 examples.
Therefore we can conclude that the number of examples in a prompt is not relevant and that GQR still works using fewer examples.

RQ5: What is the impact of the specific prompt context on the performance of our GQR system?
<br class="ltx_break"/>
To understand if the performances of GQR are conditioned by the specific examples provided in the prompt, we conduct another prompt study on Robust04.
This study tests ten prompts with two examples, each of which is unique. For instance, a prompt will be composed with examples related to a celebrity and an airline company and another one with a consumer product and a political event.
Table 8 shows that the various prompts achieve very similar effectiveness performance and they are not statistically different. Hence we can conclude that the specific query-list of recommendations prompt is not conditioning the GQR (GPT-3) generation process.
